<section id="care" style="background: var(--bg);">
    <div class="container">
        <h2 class="section-title">Complete Phalaenopsis Care Guide</h2>
        
        <div class="tabs">
            <button class="tab active" onclick="switchTab(event, 'watering')">Watering</button>
            <button class="tab" onclick="switchTab(event, 'light')">Light</button>
            <button class="tab" onclick="switchTab(event, 'fertilizing')">Fertilizing</button>
            <button class="tab" onclick="switchTab(event, 'reblooming')">Reblooming</button>
        </div>

        <div id="watering" class="tab-content active">
            <div class="tool-container">
                <h3>Watering Protocol</h3>
                <p>The #1 killer of orchids is improper watering. Here's the foolproof method:</p>
                <ul class="steps">
                    <li><strong>Check before watering:</strong> Stick your finger 1-2 inches into the potting medium. Water only when it's completely dry.</li>
                    <li><strong>The ice cube myth:</strong> Don't use ice cubes. Room temperature water only.</li>
                    <li><strong>Proper technique:</strong> Water thoroughly until water runs out the drainage holes. Let it drain completely.</li>
                    <li><strong>Frequency:</strong> Typically every 7-10 days, but always check the medium first.</li>
                    <li><strong>Never let it sit in water:</strong> Empty the decorative pot or saucer after watering.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div id="light" class="tab-content">
            <div class="tool-container">
                <h3>Light Requirements</h3>
                <p>Phalaenopsis orchids are low-light orchids, but they still need the right amount:</p>
                <ul class="steps">
                    <li><strong>Ideal location:</strong> East or west-facing window with sheer curtains.</li>
                    <li><strong>Avoid direct sunlight:</strong> Direct sun will burn the leaves. You'll see dark brown/black spots if this happens.</li>
                    <li><strong>Check leaf color:</strong> Dark green leaves = too little light. Reddish/yellowish leaves = too much light. Medium green is perfect.</li>
                    <li><strong>Artificial lighting:</strong> If natural light is limited, use LED grow lights 12-14 hours per day.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div id="fertilizing" class="tab-content">
            <div class="tool-container">
                <h3>Fertilizing Strategy</h3>
                <p>Feed your orchid to fuel healthy growth and abundant blooms:</p>
                <ul class="steps">
                    <li><strong>Formula:</strong> Use a balanced orchid fertilizer (20-20-20 or specialized orchid formula).</li>
                    <li><strong>Dilution:</strong> "Weekly, weakly" - fertilize every week at 1/4 strength.</li>
                    <li><strong>When NOT to fertilize:</strong> Never fertilize a sick, stressed, or freshly repotted orchid.</li>
                    <li><strong>Flush monthly:</strong> Once a month, water thoroughly without fertilizer to prevent salt buildup.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div id="reblooming" class="tab-content">
            <div class="tool-container">
                <h3>Reblooming Your Phalaenopsis</h3>
                <p>Getting your orchid to rebloom is 100% possible with the right approach:</p>
                <ul class="steps">
                    <li><strong>After blooms fade:</strong> Cut the spike just above the second node (bump on the stem) for potential secondary spike, or cut at base for larger blooms next time.</li>
                    <li><strong>The secret trigger:</strong> Phalaenopsis need a temperature drop to initiate blooming. 10-15¬∞F difference between day and night for 2-4 weeks.</li>
                    <li><strong>Timing:</strong> Expect new spikes in fall/winter when natural temperature drops occur.</li>
                    <li><strong>Be patient:</strong> It can take 3-6 months after the temperature trigger before you see blooms.</li>
                    <li><strong>Don't move it:</strong> Once a spike appears, don't move the plant. It can cause bud blast.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

